{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472121"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1077"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1077"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.01,0.32,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1077"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"24308"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1077"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1077"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"12362"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"645"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11129"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44932"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"24308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/24308"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 3-year-old child is brought to the Emergency Department by his mother who is concerned he has swallowed a foreign object. About 30 minutes ago her son was playing on his own with the television remote when she returned from the kitchen to see him putting an object in his mouth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe boy appears well, however he is drooling and has excess saliva in his mouth. He does not appear to be in distress or complaining of any abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the next best step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Administer lactulose","Immediate referral to ENT or Gastroenterology","Reassurance and observation","Allow the child to drink lots of water to flush any object down"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history is highly concerning of ingestion of a foreign body, in particular a button battery. Furthermore the child\u0027s excess drooling is a potential sign of foreign body ingestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EButton batteries pose a real risk as they may be active at the site of impaction and cause a localised corrosive injury. This could lead to perforation, fistula formation or stricture. In such circumstances the battery must be retrieved promptly. Button batteries need retrieval in under two hours to prevent long lasting damage and since the time of ingestion was 30 minutes ago, there is time for proper investigation after examination in the form of a \u003Cstrong\u003Echest\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray\u003C/strong\u003E to confirm the location and diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactulose\u003C/strong\u003E is a laxative used in paediatrics to prevent constipation. It has no role in helping to move on an ingested foreign body, most likely located in the oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to ENT or gastroenterolog\u003C/strong\u003Ey may be required, however given the time frame it would be wise to gather all the information about the object before planning its removal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and observation\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eingestion of water to flush object down\u003C/strong\u003E are both unsafe options, there is real concern that the child has ingested a button battery, requiring prompt and immediate attention. If the child had swallowed a less concerning foreign body than they could be admitted for observation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConcerning foreign bodies: Button batteries, large objects (\u0026gt;6cm long \u00b1 \u0026gt;2cm wide), supra-absorbant polymers, magnets, lead based objects and multi-component objects (objects where parts can separate).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Button batteries require retrieval in \u003C2hours to prevent long lasting problems or mortality","Chest X-ray is the investigation of choice for ingested foreign bodies"],"references":["Clinical Practice Guidelines : Foreign body ingestion [Internet]. Rch.org.au. 2020 [cited 15 May 2022]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Foreign_body_ingestion/","Long N. Button Battery Update [Internet]. Life in the Fast Lane \u2022 LITFL. 2020 [cited 15 May 2022]. Available from: https://litfl.com/button-battery-update/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"12362"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1077"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"12362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/12362"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-05-31T20:09:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-15T20:59:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1077"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"24308"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":